METAL CONTENT OF CONSUMER PRODUCTS TESTED BY THE NEW YORK CITY (NYC) HEALTH DEPARTMENT

Introduction:
The dataset contains the laboratory results for the consumer products samples collected from 2011 to 2022 by the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene. The New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene tests consumer products, those collected during investigations of lead poisonings and store surveys, for lead. Certain consumer products are also tested for other metals such as arsenic and mercury. The results in the dataset are representative of only the tested samples at the time they were tested.

Columns and Their Description:
a. ROW_ID: Each row ID represents unique laboratory test result for the consumer product tested.

b. PRODUCT_TYPE:
Type of consumer product tested: Cosmetics Food-Spice; Food-Candy; Food-Other Jewelry Dietary Supplement/Medications/Remedy Paint Supplies Religious powder Tableware/Pottery Toys/Childrens products QA/QC Lab test Other

c. PRODUCT_NAME:
Name of product as it appears on product label or as reported to staff during investigation.

d. METAL:
Name of metal for which product was tested: Arsenic Cadmium Lead Mercury

e. CONCENTRATION:
The amount of metal found in the sample of product tested. Sample with a metal concentration below the laboratory reporting limit is marked -1, meaning Not Detected.

f. UNITS:
Unit of measurement: ppm or parts per million mg/cm2 or milligram per square centimeter mg/L

g. MANUFACTURER:
The Name of the manufacturer as it appears on product label or as reported to staff during investigation.

h. COUNTRY_OF_ORIGIN:
Name of country where the product was made as it appears on product label or as reported to staff during investigation.

i. COLLECTION_DATE: Date the product sample was collected.

j. DELETED

OBJECTIVES

  1. To show the distribution of the different product types and continents
  2. To show the distribution of countries of origin by their continents
  3. To show product types according to their continents of origin
  4. To determine and visualize the metal contents of each product types
  5. To categorize and visualize the lead concentration of each product type and compare these concentration levels to accepted standards for each product type

TOOL USED: Ms-Excel, Python

The Units of Measurement and their meanings

ppm - Part Per Million
mg/cm^2 - Milligram per Centimetre Square
mg/l - milligram per litre
mg/kg - milligram per kilogram

In [60]:
#To check for the concentration of lead in food spices
# Filter the DataFrame for rows where the metal is 'Lead'
lead_spices = metal[(metal['Metal'] == 'Lead') & (metal['Product Type'] == 'Food-Spice')].copy()

# Categorize the lead concentration
lead_spices['Product Type'] = lead_spices['Concentration'].apply(lambda x: 'not detected' \
                                                                 if x == -1 else ('less than 1 ppm' if x < 1 else '1 ppm or higher'))

# Calculate the percentage of each category
category_percentages = lead_spices['Product Type'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
category_percentages.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'orange', 'gray'])
plt.title('Percentage of Lead Concentrations in Food Spices')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Percentage (%)')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

Half of the food spices samples contained Lead concentration that was undetectable. About 25% contained lead in the concntrations allowed and the remaining percentage consists of those that exceeded the allowed concentration limits

#To check for the concentration of lead 
# Filter the DataFrame for rows where the metal is 'Lead'
lead_powders = metal[(metal['Metal'] == 'Lead') & (metal['Product Type'] == "Religious powder" )].copy()

# Categorize the lead concentration
lead_powders['Category'] = lead_powders['Concentration'].apply(lambda x: 'not detected' if x == -1 else\
    ('less than or equal to 1 ppm' if x <= 1 else 'above 1 ppm'))

# Calculate the percentage of each category
category_percentages = lead_powders['Category'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
category_percentages.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'orange', 'grey'])
plt.title('Percentage of Lead Concentrations in Religious Powder Samples')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Percentage (%)')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.ylim(0, 100)  # Ensure the y-axis starts at 0 and ends at 100 for percentages
plt.show()

Above 65% of Religious powder samples contained Lead concentration in levels exceeding the allowed concentration.Lead was not detected in about 25% of the samples, and about 10% contained lead in concentrations within the recommended level.

FINDINGS

  1. Food Spices samples made up the larger portion of product types collected for testing
  2. A considerably large number of the products collected for testing originated from Asian countries.
  3. There are more Asian countries of origin than countries of other continents in the dataset.
  4. The most commonly found metal in the samples is Lead followed closely by Mercury. Other Metals found are Arsenic, Cadmium, and Chromium.
  5. Some food spices, candies, dietary supplements, jewelry, tableware, religious powders, toys, and other food samples contained Lead in concentrations exceeding the recommended levels. Food Spices had the higher percentage of samples that contain high Lead concentrations.

CONCLUSION

In conclusion, our analysis sheds light on the metal content of consumer products across New York City. The dominance of food spices among the samples underscores their significant presence in the local market and stores. Moreover, the prevalence of products originating from Asian countries highlights the nature of the supply chain.

The findings regarding elevated lead, mercury, and other metal concentrations in certain products that exceed recommended safety thresholds are concerning. These findings underscore potential health risks for consumers, ranging from neurological disorders and developmental delays to organ damage and cancer, and emphasize the importance of stringent regulatory measures and robust oversight to ensure product safety.
